<td>$f(x)$</td>
<td>?</td>
<td>?</td>
<td>?</td>
<td>?</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Simplifying: $\dfrac{x^2-4}{x-2} = \dfrac{(x-2)(x+2)}{x-2} = x+2$ for $x \neq 2$.<br />
$f(1{,}9)=3{,}9$; $f(1{,}99)=3{,}99$; $f(2{,}01)=4{,}01$; $f(2{,}1)=4{,}1$.<br />
$\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 2} f(x) = 4$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>By observing the graph of $f(x) = x^2 - 3x + 2$, determine intuitively $\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 1} f(x)$ and verify it by direct substitution.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Since $f$ is a polynomial (continuous on all $\mathbb{R}$), we can substitute directly:<br />
$\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 1} (x^2 - 3x + 2) = 1 - 3 + 2 = 0$.<br />
Note that $f(1) = 0$, so the limit coincides with the value of the function.</p>
</blockquote>
